1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,760
In this lesson, we're going to look at

2
00:00:02,760 --> 00:00:09,000
another numerical slash categorical plotting type called a box plot.

3
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:11,880
These are very similar to violin plots,

4
00:00:11,880 --> 00:00:14,055
but a little bit easier to interpret.

5
00:00:14,055 --> 00:00:16,530
Let's start by as always,

6
00:00:16,530 --> 00:00:20,710
importing our libraries and our dataset.

7
00:00:21,170 --> 00:00:24,015
Just like violin plots,

8
00:00:24,015 --> 00:00:26,940
box plots are used to depict

9
00:00:26,940 --> 00:00:31,125
a relationship between a quantitative and a qualitative variable.

10
00:00:31,125 --> 00:00:35,925
Both matplotlib and seaborn have a method boxplot.

11
00:00:35,925 --> 00:00:38,890
Here we're going to use seaborns.

12
00:00:38,890 --> 00:00:41,315
It takes for the data parameter,

13
00:00:41,315 --> 00:00:43,390
the data frame we're interested in.

14
00:00:43,390 --> 00:00:46,710
Our x-variable is going to be vehicle class,

15
00:00:46,710 --> 00:00:50,060
our y parameter is going to be combined

16
00:00:50,060 --> 00:00:55,205
fuel efficiency and the color I'm setting to tableau blue.

17
00:00:55,205 --> 00:01:01,595
I'm also rotating our x ticks to make our x-label easier to read.

18
00:01:01,595 --> 00:01:08,720
In a boxplot each distribution includes descriptive statistics for each category.

19
00:01:08,720 --> 00:01:14,900
For instance, each line of a box denotes a quartile range.

20
00:01:14,900 --> 00:01:22,865
For instance, this line on the box for sub-compact cars is the first quartile,

21
00:01:22,865 --> 00:01:28,310
meaning 25% of the data falls below that line.

22
00:01:28,310 --> 00:01:30,935
This middle line here is the median,

23
00:01:30,935 --> 00:01:36,025
50% of the data lives below that line, 50% above.

24
00:01:36,025 --> 00:01:41,165
Up here we have the third quartile, or 75th percentile.

25
00:01:41,165 --> 00:01:45,335
Seventy five percent of the distribution falls below that line.

26
00:01:45,335 --> 00:01:48,860
Whiskers are extended from the top and bottom of

27
00:01:48,860 --> 00:01:52,895
the boxes to indicate the largest and smallest values.

28
00:01:52,895 --> 00:01:58,180
Any outliers are indicated by these black diamonds.

29
00:01:58,180 --> 00:02:04,295
One thing to remember is that while boxplots do a fine job of summarizing the data,

30
00:02:04,295 --> 00:02:08,335
there are some distributional details that can get lost.

31
00:02:08,335 --> 00:02:12,800
In some instances, violin plots might provide more information,

32
00:02:12,800 --> 00:02:17,485
such as if distributions are bimodal or multimodal in general.

33
00:02:17,485 --> 00:02:23,035
However, filling plots can be deceiving or confusing to those not familiar with them,

34
00:02:23,035 --> 00:02:26,660
so when it comes to explanatory data visualization,

35
00:02:26,660 --> 00:02:32,220
you might want to choose a box plot for simplicity and focus.

